replies.bodyText:
I don't think forking the controller should be needed. The crux of this issue (similar to the one further down about userProvider.get()) is that we're attempting to use the same top-level controller method for two different purposes now.
Instead, one could create a private updateProfileImpl method which is called by the two top-level controller methods. With that change in place, to resolve this issue you could create a checkUserProfileUpdate method which is only called by the updateProfile top-level controller.
e.g. something like the following would be very clear
public ResponseEntity<Void> updateProfile(Profile updatedProfile) {
  validateUserProfileUpdate(updatedProfile);
  updateProfileImpl(updatedProfile, userProvider.get());
}

public ResponseEntity<Void> updateVerifiedInstitutionalAffiliation(long userId, VerifiedInstitutionalAffiliation verifiedInstitution) {
  [...]
  updateProfileImpl(updatedProfile, userDao.findUserByUserId(userId));
}

and eventually updateProfileImpl should be factored into ProfileService.

